{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "KelvinEffect",
        "description": "Kelvin effect on the equilibrium vapor pressure over a curved droplet surface — Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Chapter 10. Computes the Kelvin saturation ratio S = p_A/p°_A (Eq. 10.86), the factor by which surface curvature enhances the equilibrium vapor pressure of a small droplet relative to a flat surface: S = exp(2 σ M / (R T ρ_l R_p)). The enhancement is significant for nanometre-scale droplets and decays toward unity as the droplet radius grows. Migrated from Aerosol.jl KelvinEffect.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "seinfeld_pandis_ch10",
            "thermodynamics",
            "vapor-pressure"
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "KelvinEffect": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 10. Kelvin equation: Eq. 10.86.",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/seinfeld_pandis_ch10/kelvin_effect.jl:51\n\nUpstream `KelvinEffect` is an MTK `@component` (no parameterization). It declares one `@constants` entry (`R_gas`, the universal gas constant, 8.314 J/mol/K), five scalar `@parameters` — `T` (temperature, K), `R_p` (particle/droplet radius, m), `σ` (surface tension, N/m), `M_mol` (molar mass, kg/mol), `ρ_l` (liquid density, kg/m^3) — and two scalar `@variables` (`ln_S`, `S`, both dimensionless). The two equations are `ln_S ~ 2 σ M_mol / (R_gas T ρ_l R_p)` (the exponent of Eq. 10.86, the Kelvin equation) and `S ~ exp(ln_S)` (the saturation ratio p_A/p°_A).\n\n@constants to parameter: `R_gas` is carried as `type: parameter` with the fixed default 8.314 — the .esm schema has no constant variable type, so every MTK `@constant` migrates as a fixed-default parameter (the convention applied across the rig's prior @constant migrations). The upstream symbol name `R_gas` is kept verbatim; it is deliberately not the schema's reserved physical-constant name `R`, so the reserved-name dimensional check (`_KNOWN_PHYSICAL_CONSTANTS`) does not apply.\n\nObserved classification: KelvinEffect has no `D()` time-derivative anywhere — it is a purely-algebraic component. `ln_S` and `S` are both algebraic outputs (`ln_S ~ ...`, `S ~ exp(ln_S)`). After MTK `mtkcompile` / `structural_simplify` the compiled system has zero ODE states and both become observed quantities — the upstream `ModelingToolkit Integration` test exercises exactly this compiled form (`mtkcompile(KelvinEffect())` then `ODEProblem(compiled, [], (0.0, 1.0))`). They are therefore serialized as `type: observed` with an `expression` (not `type: state` with an equation), and the `equations` array is empty, matching the sibling pure-algebraic Aerosol.jl sp_ch10 migration `zsr.esm`. `S`'s expression references the observed `ln_S`, preserving the upstream `S ~ exp(ln_S)` two-equation structure as an observed dependency chain (`ln_S` resolves from parameters, then `S` from `ln_S`).\n\nUnicode identifiers `σ` and `ρ_l` are kept verbatim from the upstream `@parameters` declaration; the ESM identifier pattern permits unicode and the sibling sp_ch10 migration `zsr.esm` keeps the Greek symbol `α_w`, so no ASCII rename is applied. (The upstream `KelvinEffect Structure` test accepts either `:sigma` or `:σ` for the parameter name; the actual `@parameters` declaration uses `σ`.)\n\nNot migrated: the file-level helper `kelvin_saturation_ratio(T, R_p, σ, M_mol, ρ_l)` in kelvin_effect.jl is a plain Julia function — a scalar closed-form evaluator of Eq. 10.86 — not an MTK component, and is out of scope for this component migration. Its physics is identical to the component, so the upstream `Kelvin Effect Calculation` testset's limiting-case checks (large-droplet S→1, small-droplet S>1.1, temperature and surface-tension monotonicity, multi-compound applicability) are reproduced here as component-level inline tests against `ln_S`/`S`.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-8): the model is a small closed-form algebraic system — one division of two short products followed by one `exp` — so float64 evaluation roundoff is at the few-ULP (~1e-15 relative) level; rel=1e-8 leaves ample headroom."
            },
            "variables": {
                "R_gas": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/mol/K",
                    "default": 8.314,
                    "description": "Universal (ideal) gas constant — the Eq. 10.86 denominator term R. Migrated from the upstream `@constants` block; the .esm schema has no constant variable type, so it is carried as a fixed-default parameter."
                },
                "T": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 298.15,
                    "description": "Temperature of the droplet and the surrounding vapor (Eq. 10.86 term T). Appears in the exponent denominator, so a colder droplet has a larger Kelvin enhancement."
                },
                "R_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 5.0e-8,
                    "description": "Droplet (particle) radius — the radius of curvature of the liquid surface (Eq. 10.86 term R_p). The Kelvin enhancement grows as R_p shrinks and vanishes as R_p → ∞."
                },
                "σ": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "N/m",
                    "default": 0.072,
                    "description": "Surface tension of the droplet liquid (Eq. 10.86 term σ). The default 0.072 N/m is the surface tension of water near room temperature."
                },
                "M_mol": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/mol",
                    "default": 0.018,
                    "description": "Molar mass of the condensing species (Eq. 10.86 term M). The default 0.018 kg/mol is the molar mass of water."
                },
                "ρ_l": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Liquid density of the droplet (Eq. 10.86 term ρ_l). The default 1000 kg/m³ is the density of liquid water."
                },
                "ln_S": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Natural logarithm of the Kelvin saturation ratio — the exponent of Eq. 10.86: ln S = 2 σ M / (R T ρ_l R_p). Dimensionless and non-negative for physical parameters.",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    2,
                                    "σ",
                                    "M_mol"
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "R_gas",
                                    "T",
                                    "ρ_l",
                                    "R_p"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                "S": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Kelvin saturation ratio S = p_A / p°_A (Eq. 10.86): the ratio of the equilibrium vapor pressure over the curved droplet surface to that over a flat surface. S ≥ 1 — surface curvature always enhances vapor pressure — and S → 1 as R_p → ∞ (the flat-surface limit).",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "exp",
                        "args": [
                            "ln_S"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            },
            "equations": [],
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-08
            },
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "default_parameters",
                    "description": "Eq. 10.86 at the upstream default parameterization: a 50 nm water droplet at 298.15 K (σ = 0.072 N/m, M = 0.018 kg/mol, ρ_l = 1000 kg/m³). The Kelvin exponent ln S = 2σM/(R T ρ_l R_p) = 0.0209132 and the saturation ratio S = exp(ln S) = 1.021134 — a 2.1% vapor-pressure enhancement. Both outputs are algebraic and time-invariant, so the same values are asserted at t = 0 and t = 1.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "ln_S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.02091318402379585
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "ln_S",
                            "time": 1.0,
                            "expected": 0.02091318402379585
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0211333970965655
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 1.0,
                            "expected": 1.0211333970965655
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "small_droplet_strong_enhancement",
                    "description": "For a small droplet the Kelvin effect is large (upstream `S_small > 1.1`). At R_p = 10 nm — one-fifth the default radius — the exponent scales inversely with R_p to ln S = 0.104566, giving S = 1.110229, an 11% vapor-pressure enhancement.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 1.0e-8
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "ln_S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.10456592011897924
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.110228577853988
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "large_droplet_negligible_enhancement",
                    "description": "For a large droplet the Kelvin effect is negligible (upstream `S_large ≈ 1`, atol 0.002). At R_p = 1 μm — twenty times the default radius — S = 1.001046, within 0.2% of the flat-surface value.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 1.0e-6
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0010462060933767
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "macroscopic_droplet_flat_surface_limit",
                    "description": "The curved-surface enhancement vanishes in the flat-surface limit (upstream `S_very_large ≈ 1`, atol 1e-5). At R_p = 1 mm the saturation ratio S = 1.0000010 differs from unity by ~1e-6 — Eq. 10.86 reduces to p_A = p°_A as R_p → ∞.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "R_p": 1.0e-3
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.000001045659748
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "temperature_dependence",
                    "description": "Eq. 10.86 carries temperature in the exponent denominator, so a colder droplet has a larger Kelvin enhancement (upstream `S_cold > S > S_warm`). Cooling from the default 298.15 K to 250 K raises the exponent to ln S = 0.0249411 and S = 1.025255, above the default S = 1.021133.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "T": 250.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "ln_S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.024941063266778928
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0252546935814038
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "surface_tension_dependence",
                    "description": "Eq. 10.86 carries surface tension linearly in the exponent numerator, so a lower-σ liquid has a smaller Kelvin enhancement (upstream `S_high_sigma > S_low_sigma`). Reducing σ from the default 0.072 N/m to 0.030 N/m lowers the exponent proportionally to ln S = 0.0087138 and S = 1.008752, below the default S = 1.021133.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "σ": 0.03
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "ln_S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.008713826676581602
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0087519025795066
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "benzene_droplet",
                    "description": "Eq. 10.86 applies to any condensing species, not just water (upstream Table 10.6 multi-compound check `S_benzene > 1`). A 50 nm benzene droplet at 298 K (σ = 0.02821 N/m, M = 0.07811 kg/mol, ρ_l = 879 kg/m³) gives S = 1.041302 — benzene's larger molar mass outweighs its lower surface tension and density, yielding a stronger enhancement than water at the same radius.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "T": 298.0,
                        "σ": 0.02821,
                        "M_mol": 0.07811,
                        "ρ_l": 879.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "S",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.0413021421178397
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "saturation_ratio_vs_particle_radius",
                    "description": "The Kelvin saturation ratio rises steeply as the droplet shrinks (Eq. 10.86). Sweeping the particle radius R_p over the 5 nm – 1 μm range on a logarithmic axis traces S = exp(2σM/(R T ρ_l R_p)) decaying from a strong enhancement for the smallest droplets toward the flat-surface limit S → 1 for the largest.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "R_p",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 5.0e-9,
                                    "stop": 1.0e-6,
                                    "count": 50,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "s_vs_r_p",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Kelvin saturation ratio S as a function of droplet radius R_p (water droplet at the default 298.15 K).",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "R_p",
                                "label": "Droplet radius R_p (m)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "S",
                                "label": "Kelvin saturation ratio S (dimensionless)"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "saturation_ratio_vs_temperature",
                    "description": "The Kelvin enhancement weakens with temperature — Eq. 10.86 carries T in the exponent denominator. Sweeping temperature over the 250–350 K range at the default 50 nm radius traces S decreasing monotonically as the droplet warms.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "T",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 250.0,
                                    "stop": 350.0,
                                    "count": 50,
                                    "scale": "linear"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "s_vs_t",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Kelvin saturation ratio S as a function of temperature T (water droplet at the default 50 nm radius).",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "T",
                                "label": "Temperature T (K)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "S",
                                "label": "Kelvin saturation ratio S (dimensionless)"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "saturation_ratio_radius_temperature_heatmap",
                    "description": "Joint dependence of the Kelvin saturation ratio on droplet radius and temperature (Eq. 10.86). The heatmap of S(R_p, T) shows the enhancement strongest for small, cold droplets and fading toward unity for large, warm droplets.",
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "R_p",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 5.0e-9,
                                    "stop": 5.0e-7,
                                    "count": 30,
                                    "scale": "log"
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "T",
                                "range": {
                                    "start": 250.0,
                                    "stop": 350.0,
                                    "count": 25,
                                    "scale": "linear"
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "s_r_p_t_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "S(R_p, T) heatmap — Kelvin saturation ratio over droplet radius and temperature.",
                            "x": {
                                "variable": "R_p",
                                "label": "Droplet radius R_p (m)"
                            },
                            "y": {
                                "variable": "T",
                                "label": "Temperature T (K)"
                            },
                            "value": {
                                "variable": "S",
                                "reduce": "final"
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
